Introduction¶

Our topic is predicting strokes in patients using machine learning models based on collected information on patient demographics and medical history. Our goal is to analyze different features and predict if an individual is at-risk of having a stroke.

Some of the questions we are trying to answer are:

  • Can we build an accurate ML model to predict the risk of stroke in patients using available health data?
  • Which features are most relevant to risk of stroke?
  • Which machine learning model (Logistic Regression, SVM, Random Forest, etc.) performs best in terms of recall, particularly to reduce false negatives?


These questions are important because a ML tool to predict risk of stroke could be vital in enabling early detection and treatment. If our model predicts one at-risk of stroke, they can seek medical help early on and seek medical treatment to better understand and prevent future strokes. Reducing false negatives is crucial in medical applications as missing a patient who is actually at risk can lead serious bodily injury, even death. In addition, understanding which factors most influence stroke risk can help guide public health strategies, allowing society to fight strokes before they even happen.

Data Preprocessing¶






















The dataset includes several categorical variables that contain qualitiative data. Let's code this data into numbers to make it easier to work with when training our ML model. 



In addition, let's handle all the rows that contain null/missing values. We can drop them since our dataset is big and we will still have lots of data left over


















In [2]:






print("\nFirst five rows of the dataset:")
print(stroke_df.head())

#Inspect info about columns
print("\nDataFrame Info:")
stroke_df.info()

#Parse Gender into quantitative data, male to 0 and female to 1 and Other to 2
gender_map = {'Male': 0, 'Female': 1, 'Other': 2}
stroke_df['gender'] = stroke_df['gender'].apply(lambda x : gender_map[x])

#Parse ever_married into quantitative data, No to 0 and Yes to 1
stroke_df['ever_married'] = stroke_df['ever_married'].map({'No': 0, 'Yes': 1})

#Parse work_type into quantitative data, Private to 0, Self-employed to 1, Govt_job to 2, children to 3, Never_worked to 4
stroke_df['work_type'] = stroke_df['work_type'].map({'Private': 0, 'Self-employed': 1, 'Govt_job': 2, 'children': 3, 'Never_worked': 4})

#Parse Residence_type into quantitative data, Urban to 0 and Rural to 1
stroke_df['Residence_type'] = stroke_df['Residence_type'].map({'Urban': 0, 'Rural': 1})

#Parse smoking_status into quantitative data, never smoked to 0, formerly smoked to 1, smokes to 2, Unknown to 3
stroke_df['smoking_status'] = stroke_df['smoking_status'].map({'never smoked': 0, 'formerly smoked': 1, 'smokes': 2, 'Unknown': 3})

#Drop missing values
stroke_df.dropna(inplace=True)
print(stroke_df.head())

#Check for missing values
missing_values = stroke_df.isnull().sum()
print("\nMissing values in each column:\n", missing_values)

Conclusion 1:¶
I used a correlation matrix to find the correlation coefficient between the age of the patient and their history of having strokes or not. As this is a categorical variable and a quantative variable, I also used a boxplot to help better visualize the distribution of data.



We can see here that the relationship between age and having a stroke is weak and positive, as seen with a correlation coefficient of r=0.23. From this, although the correlation is weak, we can assume a positive correlation and deduct that as age increases, the risk of stroke increases as well.



To better investigate this, we can look at the boxplot, separating the data by those who have had a stroke and those who did not. Here we can see that there exists patients of all ages who have not had a stroke. There is an even distribution among all ages. However, by focusing on the right column, we can see that those who had a stroke fall in a more narrow range of ages, all of them being on the older side. 75% of patients who had a stroke are above the age of ~60 and 50% of patients who had a stroke are above the age of ~70. There is one lone outlier, but since this is just one, we can ignore it. 



Our conclusion is that strokes primarily happen to people of older ages, but being older does not necessesarily mean that you will get a stroke.






















Starting Conclusion #2¶






















Let's perform a Chi-Square Test of Independence to see if the relationship between Smoking Status and Stroke-risk is statistically significant.


















In [10]:






# Method 2: Chi-Square Test for Smoking Status vs. Stroke status
#First, create subset without Unknown smoking status
stroke_df_known_smoking = stroke_df[stroke_df['smoking_status'] != 3]

#Create a Contingency Table
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(stroke_df_known_smoking['smoking_status'], stroke_df_known_smoking['stroke'])
chi2, p, dof, ex = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
print(f"\nChi-square Test between Smoking Status and Stroke Status:")
print(f"Chi2 = {chi2:.4f}, p-value = {p}, dof = {dof}")

























Chi-square Test between Smoking Status and Stroke Status:
Chi2 = 5.9932, p-value = 0.049956999455472766, dof = 2

Conclusion #2:¶
We ran a Chi-Squared Test to test the categorical variables of Smoking Status and having a prior Stroke. The Chi-Squared Test returned a p-value of 0.04996, just under the alpha-level of 0.05, meaning we can reject the null hypothesis that there is no association. This means that we can say that there is an association between smoking and having a stroke. While the Chi-Square Test cannto reveal the direction of the association, we can say that there is an association.






















Starting Conclusion #3¶






















Let's run a T-Test to determine if the relationship between gluclose level and stroke-risk are statistically significant. The research hypothesis is that these two features are related and the null hypothesis is that these two featuers have no association. If the p-value of this T-Test is <0.05, we can reject the null hypothesis and "accept" the research hypothesis.


















In [12]:






#T-Test for Glucose Level and Stroke
#Here we are comparing the counts of the two columns, filtered by having a stroke or not
glucose_stroke = stroke_df[stroke_df['stroke'] == 1]['avg_glucose_level']
glucose_no_stroke = stroke_df[stroke_df['stroke'] == 0]['avg_glucose_level']
t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(glucose_stroke, glucose_no_stroke)
print(f"T-Statistic: {t_stat}, p-value: {p_value}")

























T-Statistic: 9.827770450292483, p-value: 1.3799691107259876e-22

























Below is a box and whisker plot displaying the glucose levels of those who had a stroke and did not have a stroke. The graph shows the medians and upper and lower quartiles, where lone dots are outliers.

Conclusion #3:¶
We ran a T-Test to compare the numerical variable of Glucose Levels and having a stroke. The T-Test returned a p-value under the alpha level 0.05, meaning we can reject the null hypothesis. This means that there is a statistically significant difference between the means of the two distributions of Glucose Levels based on if the patient had a stroke or not. This means that the Glucose Levels are different in those who had a stroke compared to those who did not have a stroke. We can conclude, based on this, that there is a correlation between Glucose Levels and having a stroke, but we cannot infer causation or direction. We also noted that there were a lot of outliers in the no-stroke distribution, which may inflate variance, inflating the p-value we got. However, since the p-value was very small, we can assume that the results are accurate and are statistically signifcant regardless.

Analysis¶
As we can see, work_type, smoking_status, bmi, gender, and Residence_type all have correlations under 0.1. However, there is a steep dropoff between bmi's correlation and the correlation values from gender and residence_type, the latter two being under 0.01. We can also see work_type, smoking_status, and bmi are low correlation scores. 



This presents an issue where we don't want to drop potentially useful data, but also don't want to have meaningless data that could cause our model to overfit. 



To solve this, we can have two sets of data: one with only the high impacting features and one where we are conservative and include borderline impacting features (like work_type, smoking_status, and bmi). We can train two models and compare their recall scores to see which one has a higher recall score - since we want to ensure that we don't miss out on any false negatives.


Additionally, based on the correlation matrix between all features:
Key predictors: Age, glucose, BMI, heart disease and hypertension are your most linearly predictive features for stroke.


Weak or non-linear relations: Work_type, smoking_status, residence_type show almost no linear correlation with stroke—if they matter, it’ll likely be in a nonlinear way or only for certain subgroups.






















ML Strategy and Selection¶
As mentioned before, we are going to check the high imipact features vs conservative ones and see how much model performance improves by adding the other features. Below is a test where we add the heavy impact feature sets then the less important ones.


















In [27]:






# 1. Define feature sets
high_feats = ['age', 'hypertension', 'heart_disease', 'avg_glucose_level', 'ever_married']
cons_feats = high_feats + ['work_type', 'smoking_status', 'bmi']

# 2. Split data (uses existing, preprocessed stroke_df)
X = stroke_df.drop(['id', 'stroke'], axis=1)
y = stroke_df['stroke']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=42
)

# 3. Train & evaluate
clf = LogisticRegression(class_weight='balanced', max_iter=1000, random_state=42)

# High-impact features
clf.fit(X_train[high_feats], y_train)
rec_high = recall_score(y_test, clf.predict(X_test[high_feats]))

# Conservative features
clf.fit(X_train[cons_feats], y_train)
rec_cons = recall_score(y_test, clf.predict(X_test[cons_feats]))

# 4. Report
print(f"Recall (High-Impact):   {rec_high:.2f}")
print(f"Recall (Conservative):  {rec_cons:.2f}")

























Recall (High-Impact):   0.68
Recall (Conservative):  0.70

























From this, we can tell that we only get +0.02 more in accuracy of true positive cases. Though this may not seem important at first, having more true positives that are detected means fewer  missed stroke patients, which is often more important than avoiding false alarms.


This tells us that Work type, smoking status, and BMI each carry a bit of additional signal that wasn’t captured by age, hypertension, heart disease, glucose, and marital status alone. Thus, going forward in our data analysis, for any ML models we should include these features.






















Why we use Logistic Regression¶
Logistic regression is ideal here because it directly models the binary outcome (stroke vs. no stroke) as a linear function based on the medical information as the features. This will give good probability scores for the binary variable and will help us determine precision scores. This will provide uys a clear benchmark before we go to more complex modeling.


















In [28]:






# Combined High-Impact + Borderline Features Logistic Regression

# 1. Compute feature–target correlations
corr_with_stroke = stroke_df.corr()['stroke'].drop('stroke')

# 2. Define high-impact (|r| > 0.10) and borderline features
high_feats       = corr_with_stroke[abs(corr_with_stroke) > 0.10].index.tolist()
borderline_feats = ['work_type', 'smoking_status', 'bmi']

# Combine them
selected_features = high_feats + borderline_feats
print("Selected features:", selected_features)

# 3. Prepare data using the combined feature set
X_sel = stroke_df[selected_features]
y     = stroke_df['stroke']

# 4. Train/test split
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train_s, X_test_s, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_sel, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# 5. Re-train logistic regression on this feature set
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
clf_sel = LogisticRegression(class_weight='balanced', max_iter=1000, random_state=42)
clf_sel.fit(X_train_s, y_train)

# 6. Evaluate
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_auc_score
y_pred_s = clf_sel.predict(X_test_s)
y_prob_s = clf_sel.predict_proba(X_test_s)[:, 1]

print("Classification Report (High-Impact + Borderline):")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_s))
print("ROC AUC (High-Impact + Borderline):", roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob_s))

weighted avg       0.95      0.76      0.83      1473

ROC AUC (High-Impact + Borderline): 0.8224361139254757

























An AUC of 0.822 means that if you randomly pick one patient who had a stroke and one who didn’t, there’s about an 82.2% chance your model will assign a higher predicted probability to the true stroke case than to the non-stroke case. This tells us that our model which includes the high impact and conservative features is able to differentiate and map the patients relation to eachother based on the stroke risk.






















Using Decision Trees¶
Decision trees automatically learn a series of “if–then” rules that split your feature space into regions of similar stroke‐risk, making them highly interpretable (“Patients older than 60 AND glucose > 120 → high risk”). There is no need to scale the data as it makes individual decisions based on trying to improve an impurity score between the decisions. This is also good because we have numerical and categorical data, so we can make these logical decisions based on thresholds.


















In [44]:






# Decision Tree Baseline

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_auc_score

# 1. Prepare data
X = stroke_df.drop(['id','stroke'], axis=1)
y = stroke_df['stroke']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=42
)

# 2. Train a balanced decision tree
clf_dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(
    max_depth=5,
    class_weight='balanced',
    random_state=42
)
clf_dt.fit(X_train, y_train)

# 3. Evaluate
y_pred_dt  = clf_dt.predict(X_test)
y_prob_dt  = clf_dt.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_dt))
print("ROC AUC:", roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob_dt))

weighted avg       0.94      0.66      0.76      1473

Improvement with Gradient Boosting¶
Gradient boosting builds an ensemble of many small trees sequentially, where each new tree corrects the errors of the previous ones. This focus on hard‐to‐predict cases generally yields higher accuracy and AUC than a single tree while still preserving some interpretability through feature‐importance scores. It’s especially effective on tabular data with mixed feature types and can automatically model complex relationships.


















In [41]:






# Gradient Boosting Classifier

from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_auc_score

# 1. (Re)use the same split defined above

# 2. Train a gradient boosting model
clf_gb = GradientBoostingClassifier(
    n_estimators=100,
    learning_rate=0.1,
    random_state=42
)
clf_gb.fit(X_train, y_train)

# 3. Evaluate
y_pred_gb = clf_gb.predict(X_test)
y_prob_gb = clf_gb.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_gb))
print("ROC AUC:", roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob_gb))

























              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.96      1.00      0.98      1410
           1       0.00      0.00      0.00        63

    accuracy                           0.96      1473
   macro avg       0.48      0.50      0.49      1473
weighted avg       0.92      0.96      0.94      1473

ROC AUC: 0.8143588877631431

























Moving from an AUC of 0.66 (our single decision‐tree model) up to 0.81 with gradient boosting means the boosted ensemble is substantially better at ranking true stroke cases above non‐stroke cases, no matter where you set your probability cutoff. Concretely, an AUC of 0.81 tells you that if you randomly pick one patient who did have a stroke and one who didn’t, the gradient-boosting model will assign a higher risk score to the true stroke patient about 81% of the time—versus only 66% for the lone decision tree. Because AUC aggregates performance over all possible thresholds, this jump shows that boosting yields a more reliable trade-off between sensitivity (catching strokes) and specificity (avoiding false alarms) across the board.

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier
from sklearn.svm import SVC

X_conservative = stroke_df.drop(['id', 'stroke', 'gender', 'Residence_type'], axis=1)
X_normal = stroke_df.drop(['id', 'stroke', 'gender', 'Residence_type', 'work_type', 'smoking_status', 'bmi'], axis=1)
y = stroke_df['stroke']

# stratified split to preserve class balance
X_train_conservative, X_test_conservative, y_train_conservative, y_test_conservative = train_test_split(
    X_conservative, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_normal, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# instantiate all models
models_conservative = {
    "Logistic Regression": LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000),
    "Decision Tree": DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=5, random_state=42),
    "Random Forest": RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),
    "SVM (RBF)": SVC(kernel='rbf', probability=True, random_state=42),
    "Gradient Boosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(
        n_estimators=100,
        learning_rate=0.1,
        random_state=42
    )
}
models = {
    "Logistic Regression": LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000),
    "Decision Tree": DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=5, random_state=42),
    "Random Forest": RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),

    "Gradient Boosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(

    )
}

#model training, resampling to account for dataset imbalance

from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)

X_train_conservative, y_train_conservative = smote.fit_resample(X_train_conservative, y_train_conservative)
for name, clf in models.items():
  clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
for name, clf in models_conservative.items():
  clf.fit(X_train_conservative, y_train_conservative)

#test to see which one we want to use
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

for name, clf in models.items():
  score = cross_val_score(clf, X_train, y_train, cv=5).mean()
  print(f"{name} Normal Score: {score:.4f}")
for name, clf in models_conservative.items():
  score = cross_val_score(clf, X_train_conservative, y_train_conservative, cv=5).mean()
  print(f"{name} Conservative Score: {score:.4f}")

Conclusions¶
Overall, stroke data is very important and represents an issue that acccounts for 11% of deaths every year. The impact of stroke detection is important at a younger age, because it can prevent issues in the future and can allow for patients to take medication and preventative measures beforehand.


Our data analysis shows us that there were a a lot of different features are very important for predicition. Ultimately, we were able to measure and predict with 81% accuracy via Gradient Boosting Trees whether patients would have a stroke or not based on our 11 features that were present in the data set. There were a lot of different models that were applied, such as a logistic regression or something else. It is very important to note that there are always ways to improve a model, but we obviously wanted to use as many features as possible to account for as many true positives (detected stroke risk) as that is the most important in a medical scenario.


As seen, using advanced models can develop complex relationships between the features for prediction purposes. There is, however limitate, which is 20% of the time where accuracy isn't correctly predicted. What this means is that there are still shortcomings in the ML predictions for stroke risk, and possible the data itself doesn't fully capture strokes and their risks to pateints around the world. Specifically, other things to note is that the data was very widespread, predicting with cases from younger children as well around the ages of 5-9, which could also affect the data.


Overall, this provides insight into the medical risks of strokes and how well the features given can tell us whether someone may be at risk of a stroke. For those new to the field of machine learning, this notebook can provide more insight into how some of these models work, like logistic regression or gradient boosting. For those who are more familiar, statistical insights and real world applications are clear: Strokes can be at least partially understood by the features we saw, and models are capable of capturing some of the statistical relevance.
